data.content:
## What happened

In C# 14, new `Span<T>`/`ReadOnlySpan<T>` conversions cause `array.Contains(num)` to bind to **`MemoryExtensions.Contains`** (span-based) instead of **`Enumerable.Contains`** (`IEnumerable<T>`-based). Expression trees cannot represent span methods, so this throws at runtime.

## How to fix

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<T>` or use `.AsEnumerable()` to force the old `Enumerable.Contains` overload:

```csharp
// Option 1: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Both approaches ensure the expression tree uses the `IEnumerable<T>` overload, which is representable in expression trees. The same issue affects `.Reverse()` on arrays — use `Enumerable.Reverse(arr)` there too.
